04262nmm a2200625Ia 9780801470264DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577424  a97808014702647 a10.7591/97808014702642doi  a(DE-B1597)478505  a(OCoLC)874563449  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJK528b.A93 201604a324.9732231 aAzari, Julia R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDelivering the People's Message :bThe Changing Politics of the Presidential Mandate /cJulia R. Azari. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresidents have long invoked electoral mandates to justify the use of executive power. In Delivering the People’s Message, Julia R. Azari draws on an original dataset of more than 1,500 presidential communications, as well as primary documents from six presidential libraries, to systematically examine choices made by presidents ranging from Herbert Hoover in 1928 to Barack Obama during his 2008 election. Azari argues that Ronald Reagan’s election in 1980 marked a shift from the modern presidency formed by Franklin Delano Roosevelt to what she identifies as a more partisan era for the presidency. This partisan model is a form of governance in which the president appears to require a popular mandate in order to manage unruly and deeply contrary elements within his own party and succeed in the face of staunch resistance from the opposition party.Azari finds that when the presidency enjoys high public esteem and party polarization is low, mandate rhetoric is less frequent and employs broad themes. By contrast, presidents turn to mandate rhetoric when the office loses legitimacy, as in the wake of Watergate and Vietnam and during periods of intense polarization. In the twenty-first century, these two factors have converged. As a result, presidents rely on mandate rhetoric to defend their choices to supporters and critics alike, simultaneously creating unrealistic expectations about the electoral promises they will be able to fulfill.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistoryy20th century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxElectionxHistoryy21st century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History.  apartisanship, Reagan administration, rhetoric in politics, political leverage, electoral mandates, use of executive power, Herbert Hoover, Barack Obama, partisan era of presidency, presidential rhetoric, presidency.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147026440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470264/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles